          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the case described, prolonged distal motor latencies and slowed conduction ve</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the case described, prolonged distal motor latencies and slowed conduction velocities on nerve conduction studies indicate damage to which component of the peripheral nerve?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cell bodies of anterior horn motor neurons</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Anterior horn cell body damage causes lower motor neuron denervation on EMG, not the demyelinating pattern of prolonged latencies seen here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Myelin sheath surrounding the axons</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Myelin insulates axons and enables saltatory conduction. In the AIDP subtype of Guillain-Barré syndrome, autoimmune destruction of peripheral myelin slows conduction velocities markedly.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Endoneurium surrounding individual nerve fibres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The endoneurium is a connective tissue layer supporting individual axons. Its damage does not produce the demyelinating pattern of prolonged latencies seen on nerve conduction studies.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vasa nervorum supplying the nerve trunk</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vasa nervorum damage causes ischaemic neuropathy, typically presenting as painful mononeuritis multiplex (e.g. in polyarteritis nodosa), not the symmetric demyelinating pattern described here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The nerve conduction findings — prolonged latencies and slowed velocities — specifically point to myelin damage. Myelin insulates axons and enables fast saltatory conduction; its loss explains the motor and sensory deficits in GBS."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. Demyelination disrupts saltatory conduction, and this is the mechanism underlying the acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy subtype of GBS."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
