          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In a cross-section of a peripheral nerve, myelinated axons appear as pale rings </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In a cross-section of a peripheral nerve, myelinated axons appear as pale rings with a central dot. What causes the pale ring appearance on routine histological staining?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Deposition of lipofuscin pigment around the axon</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lipofuscin is an ageing pigment found in neuronal cell bodies, not around axons in peripheral nerve sections.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Accumulation of Nissl substance in the Schwann cell cytoplasm</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Nissl substance (rough ER and ribosomes) is found in neuronal cell bodies and dendrites, not in Schwann cells or the myelin sheath.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Shrinkage of the myelin sheath during tissue processing</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The lipid-rich myelin dissolves and shrinks during fixation and embedding, leaving a clear halo around the central axon on the slide.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Condensation of the endoneurium around individual nerve fibres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The endoneurium is a delicate connective tissue layer around each fibre. It does not produce the characteristic pale ring; that appearance is due to myelin shrinkage during processing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The pale ring is a tissue-processing artefact. The lipid-rich myelin sheath shrinks during fixation and dehydration, leaving a clear space around the axon — a key identification feature of myelinated fibres under the microscope."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Recognising this processing artefact helps you correctly identify myelinated fibres and distinguish them from the unmyelinated Remak bundles on histological sections."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
